        <section class="mb-16">
          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">How Motorbike Loans Work in Australia</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">A motorbike loan works the same way as a car loan — you borrow a fixed amount, repay it over a set term (typically 1–7 years) with interest, and the motorcycle can serve as security for the loan (secured loan) to access lower interest rates. Motorbike finance is available from major banks, credit unions, online lenders, and specialist vehicle finance providers.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">One key difference from car loans is the typical loan amount. While the average car loan in Australia is $33,489, motorbike loans are generally smaller — ranging from $3,000 for a used scooter to $50,000+ for a new touring or adventure motorcycle. Some lenders have minimum loan amounts for secured finance (typically $5,000–$10,000), below which they only offer unsecured personal loans.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The Australian motorcycle market is healthy, with popular brands including Honda, Yamaha, Kawasaki, Suzuki, Harley-Davidson, Ducati, BMW, Triumph, KTM, and Royal Enfield. New motorcycle sales in Australia have remained strong, with adventure and learner-approved models particularly popular categories. Lenders are familiar with these brands and their resale values, which influences both approval likelihood and interest rates offered.</p>
        </section>

