          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Tips for Getting the Best Motorbike Loan</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Choose a secured loan if the bike value is above the lender's minimum threshold (typically $5,000–$10,000). Secured rates are substantially lower than unsecured — the difference can be 3–5% p.a. or more. For lower-value bikes and scooters where secured finance is not available, compare unsecured personal loan options.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Keep the loan term as short as you can comfortably afford. Motorcycles depreciate faster than cars, and a 7-year loan on a bike that depreciates quickly creates a risk of negative equity. A 3–5 year term is usually a good balance between affordable monthly repayments and total interest cost.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Budget for insurance. Comprehensive motorcycle insurance is typically required by lenders for secured loans. Motorcycle insurance premiums vary significantly by rider age, licence type, bike category, and location. For sport bikes ridden by younger riders, premiums can be substantial — factor this into your total ownership cost.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-16">
          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Business Use Motorcycle Finance</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">If you use a motorcycle primarily for business — courier work, food delivery, farm use, or commuting to client sites — a chattel mortgage may be the better option. Like a car chattel mortgage, you can claim GST on the purchase, deduct interest, and claim depreciation. This is particularly relevant for delivery riders who use motorcycles and scooters as their primary business tool.</p>
        </section>
